"use strict";(self.webpackChunk_N_E=self.webpackChunk_N_E||[]).push([[5694],{35694:function(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('[{"id":"q1","category":"Theory","question":"The Hosting Layer spec shows a multi-stage Dockerfile (builder stage → production stage). Why does this produce a smaller, more secure image than a single-stage build?","options":["Multi-stage builds apply zstd compression to the final image layers automatically","The builder stage installs compilers, TypeScript, devDependencies, and build tools — only the compiled output (dist/) and production node_modules are COPY\'d into the lean runtime stage, so those build tools never exist in the production image","Docker automatically removes duplicate layers across stages using content-addressable storage","Multi-stage builds enable read-only filesystem mode which prevents runtime code injection"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec shows: Stage 1 (builder) — `FROM node:20 AS builder`, installs all deps, runs `npm run build`. Stage 2 (production) — `FROM node:20-slim`, copies only `dist/` and `node_modules/` (production deps only). The result: a 200MB image instead of 1.2GB. Security improves because no compiler, TypeScript, or dev tooling exists in production — an attacker who breaks in can\'t compile new code. The checklist mandates \'Docker multi-stage builds\' and \'non-root user in containers.\'","hint":"What tools are needed to BUILD your app vs to RUN it? Does production need TypeScript, webpack, or test frameworks?"},{"id":"q2","category":"Theory","question":"The Hosting Layer\'s Blue-Green deployment diagram shows the old (Blue) environment kept running after switching 100% of traffic to Green. Why is Blue kept alive rather than immediately terminated?","options":["Blue serves as a read replica for the database during the switchover window","Blue handles long-lived WebSocket connections that Green cannot take over mid-session","Blue enables instant rollback — if Green has a critical bug discovered after go-live, the load balancer switches back to Blue immediately with zero re-deploy time, cutting the incident window from 20+ minutes to seconds","Blue\'s health checks run against Green\'s endpoints to validate the switchover was successful"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec describes Blue-Green as: \'switch load balancer instantly, keep old running for rollback.\' The key property is: Blue is proven-working production code still running and warm. If Green has a database migration bug, a memory leak, or an API regression that only appears under real traffic, the rollback is one DNS/load balancer change — no rebuild, no re-deploy. The spec recommends keeping Blue alive for at least 30 minutes after traffic switch before decommissioning.","hint":"If Green has a critical bug discovered 10 minutes after going live, what makes Blue-Green rollback faster than redeploying the old version?"},{"id":"q3","category":"Practical","question":"Identify the TWO most critical production problems in this Dockerfile:","code":"FROM node:20\\n\\nWORKDIR /app\\nCOPY . .\\nRUN npm install\\nRUN npm run build\\n\\nEXPOSE 3000\\nCMD [\\"node\\", \\"dist/server.js\\"]","codeLanguage":"dockerfile","options":["`EXPOSE 3000` should be `EXPOSE 8080` and `npm install` should use `--production` flag","The container process runs as root (CVE risk — if compromised, attacker has root in container) AND there is no multi-stage build (devDependencies, TypeScript source, and build tools all ship to production, bloating the image ~5x)","`WORKDIR /app` should be `WORKDIR /usr/src/app` and CMD should use `npm start`","Missing `.dockerignore` causes slow build context upload; `COPY . .` should come after `npm install` for better layer caching"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec\'s Hosting checklist mandates: (1) \'Non-root user in containers\' — add `RUN addgroup -S app && adduser -S app -G app` and `USER app` before CMD. A container running as root means a container breakout gives the attacker root on the host. (2) \'Docker multi-stage builds\' — a single-stage build ships all devDependencies and TypeScript source. A typical Node app goes from ~1.2GB (single stage) to ~200MB (multi-stage) by copying only `dist/` and pruned production modules.","hint":"Check two things: what user runs the process inside the container, and what files are present in the final production image?"},{"id":"q4","category":"Practical","question":"During a Canary deployment at 5% traffic, your monitoring dashboard shows the canary pods have 3x the error rate of the stable version. The pipeline is about to advance to 25% automatically. What should happen according to the spec?","options":["Continue — 5% traffic is statistically too small a sample to make a reliable decision","Automatically halt the rollout, roll back canary pods to the stable version, fire an alert to the on-call engineer, and require a manual approval gate before any further deployment","Restart the canary pods to clear any transient startup errors, then re-evaluate","Continue routing only synthetic/bot traffic to canary while advancing real user traffic to the stable version"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec documents Canary deployment as: \'5% → 25% → 50% → 100% with metric monitoring at each stage.\' A 3x error rate increase is a clear regression signal — the pipeline must: (1) halt immediately before more users are affected, (2) roll back the 5% canary to stable (most users were never on the bad version), (3) alert on-call, (4) require human review before re-attempting. The spec notes: \'Rollback procedure tested\' and \'Deployment notifications\' as checklist items.","hint":"The whole point of canary deployment is to catch problems at low blast radius — what should the automated system do when the canary\'s metrics show a clear regression?"},{"id":"q5","category":"Theory","question":"According to the Hosting Production Checklist, where must application secrets (database passwords, JWT signing keys, API keys) be stored?","options":["In environment variables defined directly in the Dockerfile with `ENV DB_PASSWORD=...`","In a `.env` file in the repository root with file permissions set to 600 for security","In a secrets manager (AWS Secrets Manager, HashiCorp Vault) fetched at runtime startup — secrets must never be baked into images, committed to version control, or stored in environment variable definitions in Dockerfiles","Base64-encoded in `docker-compose.yml` environment variables to obfuscate them from casual inspection"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec mandates: \'Secrets in secrets manager\' and \'Environment variables validated at startup.\' Baking secrets into images means anyone with docker pull access has the secrets. Committing to git means they\'re in git history forever. The spec\'s pattern: container starts, calls AWS Secrets Manager / Vault at boot, loads secrets into environment variables in memory only — never on disk or in the image layers. The `env-validation` snippet in the spec validates at startup that all required secrets are present.","hint":"If a secret is in a Docker image layer, who can access it? What about git history — can you truly delete a committed secret?"}]')}}]);